<article>
    <h1>Cul&#xAD;ture and cof&#xAD;fee in the south</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201122/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-22"><time>2020-11-22</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The Cen­tral Busi­ness District (CBD) is a ghost town on week­ends – per­fect for a so­cially dis­tanced out­ing.</p>
    <p>We were pleas­antly sur­prised by the amount of thought that had gone into de­sign­ing the fun and in­ter­ac­tive ex­hi­bi­tion at Sin­ga­pore Chi­nese Cul­tural Cen­tre (top, 1 Straits Boule­vard), a treat for both the young and old. Ad­mis­sion is free.</p>
    <p>Don’t for­get to head up to the rooftop for a view of the Sin­ga­pore Strait be­fore leav­ing. Then cross the road to grab a cuppa from cult cof­fee stand Omote­sando Kof­fee (above, 04-01,</p>
    <p>6A Shen­ton Way) at OUE Down­town to sip on as you make your way to Nude Seafood at</p>
    <p>Ma­rina One East Tower (01-23, 5 Straits View), a seven-minute walk away.</p>
    <p>It was rain­ing the af­ter­noon we were there, the per­fect weather to dig into its Grand­fa­ther’s pom­fret soup, prob­a­bly the clos­est one can get to home-cooked com­fort food in the CBD.</p>
    <p>Take a ca­sual am­ble through Ma­rina One’s (7 Straits View) breath­tak­ingly fu­tur­is­tic tiered gar­den de­signed by Amer­i­can land­scape ar­chi­tect Kathryn Gustafson af­ter lunch.</p>
    <p>Then con­tinue with a five-minute stroll over to The Promon­tory for some green space, flanked by a spec­tac­u­lar city sky­line.</p>
    <p>If your chil­dren are not too tired, take your pick of the nu­mer­ous wa­ter­front bars nearby to wind down at ap­ero hour.</p>

